\begin_layout Standard
(1
\begin_inset Formula $\implies$
\end_inset

2): Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 be non-empty open subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $U\cap V=\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $(X\backslash U)\cup(X\backslash V)=X$
\end_inset

 contradicts the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is irreducible.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(2
\begin_inset Formula $\implies$
\end_inset

3): Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 be a non-empty open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X\backslash\overline{U}$
\end_inset

 are disjoint open subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is non-empty, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $X\backslash\overline{U}=\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\overline{U}$
\end_inset

 which means 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is dense in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(2
\begin_inset Formula $\implies$
\end_inset

4): Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 be a non-empty open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is not connected: write 
\begin_inset Formula $U=(U_{1}\cap U)\cup(U_{2}\cap U)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{2}$
\end_inset

 are open subsets in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}\cap U\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{2}\cap U\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 This is a contradiction since 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}\cap U$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{2}\cap U$
\end_inset

 are non-empty open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 which have non-empty intersection.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(3
\begin_inset Formula $\implies$
\end_inset

5): Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 be a non-empty open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 We show that every non-empty open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is dense in 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 (this shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is irreducible).
 Now 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is also open in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and therefore dense in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 But then 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is certainly dense in 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

