\begin_layout Section
Quasi-Compact and Noetherian Topological Spaces
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is called 
\series bold
quasi-compact 
\series default
if every open covering of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 has a finite subcovering.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is called 
\series bold
Noetherian 
\series default
if every descending chain 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X\supseteq Z_{1}\supseteq Z_{2}\supseteq\cdots
\]

\end_inset

of closed subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 becomes stationary, i.e.
 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{\lambda}=Z_{\lambda+1}=Z_{\lambda+2}=\cdots$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\geq1$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a topological space.
 The following are equivalent:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is Noetherian.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Every non-empty set of closed subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 has a minimal element.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Every non-empty set of open subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 has a maximal element.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The equivalence of (2) and (3) is trivial.
 Let us show that (1) is equivalent to (2).
 First assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is Noetherian and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{F}$
\end_inset

 be a non-empty family closed subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{F}$
\end_inset

 has no minimal element.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{F}$
\end_inset

 is nonempty, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{0}\in\mathscr{F}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{F}$
\end_inset

 has no minimal element, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{1}\in\mathscr{F}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{0}\supset Z_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Again since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{F}$
\end_inset

 has no minimal element, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{2}\in\mathscr{F}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{0}\supset Z_{1}\supset Z_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Continuing in this way, we obtain a descending chain of closed subsets
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Z_{0}\supset Z_{1}\supset Z_{2}\supset\cdots,
\]

\end_inset

which does not become stationary.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Conversely, suppose that every non-empty set of closed subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 has a minimal element.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
X\supseteq Z_{1}\supseteq Z_{2}\supseteq\cdots\label{eq:chainofdescending}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

be a descending chain of closed subsets.
 Then the 
\begin_inset Formula $\{Z_{i}\}_{i\in\mathbb{N}}$
\end_inset

 is a non-empty family of closed subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, and hence must have a minimal element.
 This implies that the chain 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:chainofdescending})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 becomes stationary.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemma1.24}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a topological space that has a finite covering 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\bigcup_{i=1}^{r}X_{i}$
\end_inset

 by Noetherian subspaces.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is itself Noetherian.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X\supseteq Z_{1}\supseteq Z_{2}\supseteq\cdots
\]

\end_inset

be a descending chain of closed subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Then for each 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, we obtain a descending chain of closed subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}:$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X_{i}\supseteq Z_{1}\cap X_{i}\supseteq Z_{2}\cap X_{i}\supseteq\cdots.
\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}$
\end_inset

 is Noetherian, this chain must terminate, say at 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{\lambda_{i}}\cap X_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=\max_{i}(\lambda_{i})$
\end_inset

.
 Then for any 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\geq\lambda$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
Z_{\mu} & =X\cap Z_{\mu}\\
 & =\left(\bigcup_{i=1}^{r}X_{i}\right)\cap Z_{\mu}\\
 & =\bigcup_{i=1}^{r}\left(X_{i}\cap Z_{\mu}\right)\\
 & =\bigcup_{i=1}^{r}\left(X_{i}\cap Z_{\mu+1}\right)\\
 & =\left(\bigcup_{i=1}^{r}X_{i}\right)\cap Z_{\mu+1}\\
 & =Z_{\mu+1}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemma1.25}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a Noetherian topological space.
 Then
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Every subspace of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is Noetherian.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Every open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is quasi-compact (in particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is quasi-compact).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Every closed subset 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\subseteq X$
\end_inset

 has only finitely many irreducible components.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 be a subspace of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and suppose 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Z\supseteq Z\cap Z_{1}\supseteq Z\cap Z_{2}\supseteq\cdots
\]

\end_inset

is a descending chain of closed subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X\supseteq Z_{1}\supseteq Z_{2}\supseteq\cdots
\]

\end_inset

is a descending chain of closed subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is Noetherian, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{\mu}=Z_{\mu+1}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\geq\lambda$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\geq1$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, this implies 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\cap Z_{\mu}=Z\cap Z_{\mu+1}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\geq\lambda$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\geq1$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
By (1), it suffices to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is quasi-compact.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 be an open cover of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{U}$
\end_inset

 be the set of those open subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 that are finite unions of the subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is Noetherian, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{U}$
\end_inset

 has a maximal element 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 Clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $V=X$
\end_inset

, otherwise there existed an 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is properly contained in 
\begin_inset Formula $V\cup U_{i}\in\mathcal{U}$
\end_inset

.
 This shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 has a finite subcovering.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
It suffices to show that every Noetherian space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 can be written as a finite union of irreducible subsets.
 If the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 of closed subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 that cannot be written as a finite union of irreducible subsets were non-empty,
 there existed a minimal element 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\in\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
 The set 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 is not irreducible and thus is the union of two proper closed subsets which
 do not lie in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
 This leads to a contradiction.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X\subseteq\mathbb{A}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 be any subspace.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is Noetherian.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 By 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{lemma1.25})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 it suffices to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 is Noetherian.
 But descending chains of closed subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 correspond to ascending chains of radical ideals of 
\begin_inset Formula $k[T_{1},\dots,T_{n}]$
\end_inset

.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $k[T_{1},\dots,T_{n}]$
\end_inset

 is Noetherian by Hilbert's basis theorem, this proves the proposition.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Dimension
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a (non-empty) irreducible topological space.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Chain}(X)$
\end_inset

 denote the set of all 
\series bold
chains of irreducible closed subsets 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, that is, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{Chain}(X):=\{\wp=(\emptyset\neq X_{0}\subset X_{1}\subset\cdots\subset X_{n}\subset X)\mid X_{i}\mbox{ is irreducible closed subset of }X\}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\wp=(\emptyset\neq X_{0}\subset X_{1}\subset\cdots\subset X_{n}\subset X)\in\text{Chain}(X)$
\end_inset

, then 
\series bold
length
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $(\wp):=n$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The 
\series bold
dimension 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{dim}(X)=\sup\{\mbox{length}(\wp)\mid\wp\in\text{Chain}(X)\}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is any Noetherian topological space, then the dimension of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is defined to be the supremum of the dimensions of its irreducible components.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A space of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
curve 
\series default
and a space of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
surface
\series default
.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X=V(T_{1}T_{3},T_{2}T_{3})$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1}=V(T_{3})$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{2}=V(T_{1},T_{2})$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{2}$
\end_inset

 are the irreducible components of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 One can show that a maximal chain of irreducible closed subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1}$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\wp_{1}=(V(T_{1},T_{2},T_{3})\subset V(T_{1},T_{3})\subset V(T_{3})),
\]

\end_inset

and thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{dim}(X_{1})=2$
\end_inset

.
 Similary one can show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{dim}(X_{2})=1$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{dim}(X)=2$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

